Turkey's diplomatic horizons are widening
Long before Turkey began trying to join the European Union, they wanted the European powers to penetrate deep into Turkey’s borders.
On the eastern bank of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this unsuccessful imperial ambition.
The Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Con in neo-Renaissance style.
That's what the tour guides will tell you.
The building sits roundabout at the end of the footpath with towers at each corner of the front, looking at the indiscriminate view from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vaulted cash register, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gate the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium of the Anatolian-Baghdadi Corporation.
Germany, which became involved in the game of empires late, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East by means of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad, and on to the territory that is now Saudi Arabia.
But the German imperial ambitions collapsed during the First World War.
Their ranks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular units.
Relative isolation from surrounding areas, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone
British and colonial forces advanced from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And bad news also came for Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a station.
In 1917, the explosion of a munitions train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was a sabotage.
Since then, they have been gradually drooling and history has been bypassing them.
However, today this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from surrounding areas, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
A new policy is now in place - Turkey is getting involved.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital of Ankara, where I was supposed to meet one of the leading ACP experts on foreign policy, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a hilly ride on the railways, reminiscent of the old-world rhythms of the famous document Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn to its Ottoman past.
But the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
In the West, it has aroused suspicion, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP’s main tent, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, purposely built on a developing suburb, surrounded by half-detached storehouses and shops to power, where middle managers in business suits – men and women – meet to snuggle around.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost every other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
“The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its borders.
Today we have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He had to do both.
'But surely the time will come, 'I asked myself, 'when might Turkey have to decide?'
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want such a decision to take place."
Then he pointed out that almost everyone I spoke to here said almost in memory: Turkish relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea area are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, travel along these tracks east to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpa<0xC5><0xA1>a station, after most of the night's sleep, I thought of the two German masters Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched the building build a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be if they found that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East could now be, in large part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited in the port for the ferry back across the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was not much doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
