"Car Bee" Prevents Collisions
To make progress in the development of technology to protect against accidents, Nissan this time was inspired by nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the example of flying bees, and thus prevents crashes.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C, which represents the first step in precipitation prevention technologies.
The engineers of the Nissan Motor Co. Robotics Center for Technical Progress have developed the prestigious Japanese University of Tokyo, in collaboration with the Center for Progress in Science and Technology Research.
According to Kazuhira Doie, director general of public relations for technology, research and brand development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four safety shield zones.
The robot aims to strengthen the ability to prevent precipitation in cars of this brand.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, which allows the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
When creating this visual feature, engineers designed what they called a laser range finder (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles up to a distance of two metres in a 180-degree radius before the BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a collision warning.
“The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the movements of the bees and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and to the direction in which it is allowed to rotate its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to accelerating and slowing down, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from collapsing.
“The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and maintain itself according to this data.
It does not require the retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just two dozen kB of memory.
It may surprise you, but we’re not talking about the giga or the mega.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for the immediate prevention of precipitation, a technology where Nissan predicts the use of mass-produced cars in ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination and avoid obstacles on the way.
