A week after unveiling their preliminary agreement, the two banks explained that MUFG intends to buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley’s common stock at a unit price of $25.25, representing a total of $3 billion.
The agreed price is 19% lower than the book value of the securities as of 31 August.
MUFG is investing another $6 billion to acquire convertible securities, which will provide it with a 10% return and whose exchange price is $31.25.
Morgan Stanley has specified that the entire operation will take place on the basis of an average unit price of $29, i.e. 28% below its current rate.
Morgan Stanley's shares, however, lost 6.79% and rose to $23.07 around 17.00 Greenwich time.
“This strategic merger represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to banking holding status,” said John Mack, the group’s CEO.
Morgan Stanley adopted the new statute last week, which would allow him to diversify his activities, but at the same time it puts him under the supervision of the Federal Reserve Bank.
His merger with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest ace from Wall Street to take a far more cautious approach than before.
Conditions presented on Monday show, among other things, that the deal has been changed over the past few days: last Monday Morgan only announced that he would sell up to 20% of his shares to the Japanese for about $8.5 billion.
"A week ago we thought," Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained in Tokyo, "that our participation would consist exclusively of ordinary shares.
However, given the current situation of the economy and the market, we wanted to minimize the risks and also to cover ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will pay Morgan Stanley securities 7% less than their carrying amount.
And the operation will result in a reduction in earnings from the stock by about 20%.
The agreement assumes that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferred securities into ordinary shares in a year if the latter are exchanged for a certain period of time at a price of 50% above the exchange rate, i.e. around $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital that MUFG will bring will allow him to take advantage of investment opportunities, strengthen his balance sheet and raise his cash.
However, the groups refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
Following MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should boast a Tier One payout ratio of around 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said he had "significantly" cut his balance sheet since the end of August.
The last few weeks have been challenging for the group, as its exchange rate has halved, while the insurance costs against the risk of default associated with debt have risen sharply.
On Monday, these costs took the opposite course, but remained high, at around 12%.
Last week, Goldman Sachs, the only other “survivor” of Wall Street’s major investment banks after the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced it had raised $15 billion, in part from Berkshire Hathaway, Warren Buffett’s group.
Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Re-establishing a republic around 21st century socialism.
Such is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivian Eva Morales and Ecuador Rafael Correy.
Last Sunday, the third nominee submitted to the vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, a proposal for a new Constitution.
And his mission is fulfilled, as 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the votes, voted in the referendum "yes".
According to these results, "No" gained 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% of the ballots were empty.
In order to pass the Constitution, he had to get half the votes plus one.
Two polls conducted in the east of the polling stations and a tally of NGOs predicted a clear "yes" victory on Sunday, ranging from 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa, after all, on the night of Sunday to Monday, demanded the victory of his draft Constitution.
"The Constitution has won on the whole line," he assured and congratulated the Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa received his congratulations from Chavez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission took place peacefully, concerned a text on 444 points building a “new socialism” promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution devolves the power of the state over the economy by reserving it from the "development planning" of a country living mainly from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and from the exchange rates sent by its emigrants.
The Correou-protected proposal, which was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, who will be able to carry out two consecutive four-year mandates and be able to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that it will exercise this power and apply for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution, among other things, reinforces the principle of free health and education that the president began to introduce in a country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also envisages a ban on the presence of foreign troops, thus ending the agreement between Washington and Quito on the use of the Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
In Chad, 19 hostages were released.
The Egyptian commando attacked the kidnappers of eleven tourists and their eight-member escort, who were captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were taken alive and well to Egypt’s capital on Monday.
During the morning, an Egyptian commando was liberated in Chad.
The hostages arrived around 3:30 p.m., apparently in good shape, on board a special aircraft at al-Maza military base, close to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported, without having the opportunity to speak in the press, aboard a helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, the outskirts of Cairo’s residential district, to undergo medical examinations there.
"They are completely healthy" and "no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers," Egypt's tourism minister Zohehir Garran said on the airport's runway.
Since being captured on September 19 during a four-wheel drive safari at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard director of the agency Aegyptous, a safari organizer.
A senior Egyptian security official suggested that 30 members of the special forces, who approached the site on board two helicopters, had gone on strike during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shooting, half of the kidnappers were killed and the others fled," said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He suggested that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces from the "flash" unit were sent to Sudan, where they gained the support of German and Italian teams.
The head of Italian diplomacy, Franco Frattini, from Belgrade, where he is located, mentioned the role played by secret agents and components of the Italian special forces.
"We have to acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the people from our secret services, from the special forces," he said without further specifying.
He also denied that the ransom would be paid.
The Sudanese army said on Monday it had detained a four-wheeled vehicle carrying the hijackers, killing six of them, including a Chadian commander and arresting two.
The army claimed to have been linked to a group of rebels in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement - Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately rejected.
